  <section class="lsl-section">
    <p class="lsl-secondary-label">Supporting &middot; why the tactic matters less over time</p>
    <h2>The upper channel is vanishing</h2>
    <div class="lsl-prose">
      <p>The tactical edge <em>per opportunity</em> stays large &mdash; up high, laddering still wins big. But the opportunities to be up high are collapsing cycle over cycle. Maximum channel position reached, by four-year window:</p>
    </div>
    <div class="lsl-table-wrap">
      <table class="lsl-table">
        <thead><tr><th>Window</th><th>Max channel position</th></tr></thead>
        <tbody id="lslCompressionBody"></tbody>
      </table>
    </div>
    <div class="lsl-prose">
      <p>As Bitcoin matures it increasingly lives low-to-mid channel, where decisiveness wins &mdash; consistent with the volatility compression on <a href="/the-doubling-ladder">The Doubling Ladder</a> and the Power Law&rsquo;s shrinking cycle peaks. The clever &ldquo;wait-and-ladder-down-from-the-top&rdquo; move is one you rarely get to use anymore. The channel mostly just says <em>commit</em>.</p>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- ════════ HONESTY LAYER ════════ -->
  <section class="lsl-section">
    <div class="belief-context">
      <div class="belief-context-label">A note on prerequisite reading</div>
      <p><strong>This tool uses the Power Law channel to frame the decision.</strong> If that model isn&rsquo;t useful to you, neither is this page. <a href="/the-power-law#channel">The Channel</a> lays out the bands, the evidence, and the attribution &mdash; read it first if the frame is new.</p>
    </div>

    <h3>Where the clean backtest doesn&rsquo;t describe you</h3>
    <div class="lsl-caveats">
      <div class="lsl-caveat">
        <h4>The Power Law is empirical, not guaranteed.</h4>
        <p>It&rsquo;s an observation that has held across fifteen years and nine orders of magnitude &mdash; not a promise. Future cycles aren&rsquo;t assured, and every projection assumes the channel&rsquo;s mathematical shape keeps holding.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="lsl-caveat">
        <h4>Hindsight flatters the fit.</h4>
        <p>The bands were drawn through the data, which makes &ldquo;buy low in the channel&rdquo; look prescient. The backtest is what <em>would have</em> happened; past cycles aren&rsquo;t promised to the next buyer.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="lsl-caveat lsl-caveat-blindspot">
        <h4>The math ignores the panic threshold.</h4>
        <p>The backtest says deploying usually wins &mdash; but it models a holder who never sells in fear. A real person who lump-sums and watches a 30% drawdown may capitulate and leave entirely. That&rsquo;s the model&rsquo;s blind spot, not an edge, and it&rsquo;s the honest case for laddering even when the channel says deploy. It sits with the live reading above for a reason.</p>
      </div>
    </div>

    <ul class="negative-space-list">
      <li><strong>Not a price target.</strong> The page never tells you where price is going &mdash; only how to weigh deployment given where price <em>is</em> in the channel.</li>
      <li><strong>Not a trading strategy.</strong> The only endorsed tactic is adjusting deployment decisiveness by valuation. Getting in, not trading in and out.</li>
      <li><strong>Not a timing signal.</strong> &ldquo;Decisive&rdquo; and &ldquo;hedge&rdquo; are about valuation, not a prediction that a move is imminent.</li>
    </ul>
  </section>

  <!-- ════════ METHODOLOGY ════════ -->
  <div class="lsl-attribution">
    <span class="lsl-attribution-label">Channel framework &amp; coefficients</span>
    The Power Law channel &mdash; floor at 0.42&times; trend, upper band at 3&times; trend &mdash; was developed by <a href="https://www.porkopolis.io/thechart/" target="_blank" rel="noopener"><strong>Matthew Me&zcaron;inskis</strong></a> at Porkopolis Economics. Coefficients used: <code>a = 1.6&times;10<sup>&minus;17</sup></code>, <code>b = 5.77</code>. See <a href="/the-power-law#channel">The Channel</a> for the full case and attribution.
  </div>

  <div class="lsl-method">
    <div class="lsl-method-label">Methodology</div>
    <ul>
      <li>Channel position is the log-space location between floor and ceiling: <code>(ln(price/trend) &minus; ln 0.42) / (ln 3.0 &minus; ln 0.42)</code> &mdash; 0 at the floor, 1 at the upper band.</li>
      <li>Backtest: a fixed sum deployed all-at-once vs. laddered equally across the chosen window, comparing BTC accumulated, bucketed by entry channel position. The advantage is amount-invariant.</li>
      <li>Commitment backstop: mean value-multiple by hold length. <strong>8-year exit convention</strong> &mdash; the nearest sample to (entry&nbsp;+&nbsp;8&nbsp;&times;&nbsp;365.25&nbsp;days); carries ~1&ndash;3% sensitivity (disclosure, not precision). Worst-entry recovery is the range for entries above 1.5&times; channel position (roughly the 2011/2013 blow-off tops), recovered to the latest sample.</li>
      <li id="lslMethodWindow"></li>
      <li>Today&rsquo;s channel position is computed at load from the latest sample and the live spot (CoinGecko, via the shared fetch) &mdash; never baked in. Forward scenarios calibrated to recent-era amplitude are a Stage 2B addition.</li>
    </ul>
  </div>

